SEER ✅Assessing incidence or survival outcomes for cancers by patient demographic. ❌Assessing perioperative data and postoperative outcomes. ❌For pancreas surgeons, limited robotic PD numbers, PA and NC are not SEER states...

OSHPC (CA), SPARCS (NY) etc ✅Assessing long-term healthcare utilization for conditions or after procedures, benchmarking outcomes, policy ?s. has done amazing work with these for reference. ❌Any cancer-related topic, no staging information / pathologic variables.

NCDB ✅Correlating pathologic variables / treatment sequences with survival outcomes. has been a master at this. ❌Describing disparities in treatment or outcomes (it's like looking at who's poor amongst millionaires, pts seen at non-CoC hospitals not included).

NIS ✅Picking up signals in inpatient setting requiring large numbers (this is a very limited database, there is almost always a better dataset for any topic imo..) ❌Analyzing trends in treatment or outcomes with study period crossing 2011.

NSQIP ✅Investigating immediate postoperative outcomes like LOS, wound infection rates, etc. has been masters at this. ❌Analyzing survival outcomes/comparing treatment where missing non-operative cases in your denominator would pose a problem.
